<DocsLayout title="Job Chaining">
  <h1>Job Chaining</h1>
  <p>
    Job chaining lets you express dependencies between encoding jobs so that one job only starts after one or more predecessor jobs have completed successfully. This is the foundation for multi-stage pipelines such as analyse → encode → normalise → merge.
  </p>

  <h2>Concepts</h2>

  <h3>depends_on</h3>
  <p>
    Every job may carry a <code>depends_on</code> list — an array of job IDs that must reach the <code>completed</code> status before the current job is eligible for dispatch. A job with unsatisfied dependencies is placed in the <code>waiting</code> status and is invisible to agents until all predecessors finish.
  </p>
  <p>
    Dependencies are checked by the Controller's scheduler on every status transition. When all listed predecessors complete, the dependent job transitions from <code>waiting</code> to <code>queued</code> and becomes eligible for agent pickup.
  </p>

  <h3>chain_group</h3>
  <p>
    A <code>chain_group</code> is a named, opaque label shared by all jobs in the same pipeline. It serves two purposes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>It lets you fetch all jobs belonging to a pipeline in a single API call (<code>GET /api/v1/job-chains/&#123;chain_group&#125;</code>).</li>
    <li>It is the cancellation unit — cancelling a chain group cancels every non-terminal job that belongs to it.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Typical Workflow</h2>
  <pre><code>┌─────────────┐
│  Analysis   │  job_1  (MediaInfo + HDR detect)
└──────┬──────┘
       │ depends_on: []
       ▼
┌─────────────┐
│   Encode    │  job_2  (ChunkedEncode with adaptive chunking)
└──────┬──────┘
       │ depends_on: [job_1]
       ▼
┌─────────────┐
│    Audio    │  job_3  (LoudnessAnalyse → AudioNormalise)
└──────┬──────┘
       │ depends_on: [job_1]
       ▼
┌─────────────┐
│    Merge    │  job_4  (AudioMerge + FileOutput)
└─────────────┘
       │ depends_on: [job_2, job_3]</code></pre>
  <p>
    Jobs 2 and 3 both depend only on job 1, so they can run in parallel once analysis completes. Job 4 waits for both jobs 2 and 3 before the merge step runs.
  </p>

  <h2>API Reference</h2>

  <h3>Create a Job Chain</h3>
  <pre><code>POST /api/v1/job-chains
Content-Type: application/json

&#123;
  "chain_group": "movie-2024-encode",
  "jobs": [
    &#123;
      "id": "job_1",
      "name": "Analysis",
      "flow": "analyse-hdr",
      "source_id": "src_abc123",
      "depends_on": []
    &#125;,
    &#123;
      "id": "job_2",
      "name": "Video Encode",
      "flow": "encode-4k-hdr10",
      "source_id": "src_abc123",
      "depends_on": ["job_1"]
    &#125;,
    &#123;
      "id": "job_3",
      "name": "Audio Normalise",
      "flow": "audio-r128",
      "source_id": "src_abc123",
      "depends_on": ["job_1"]
    &#125;,
    &#123;
      "id": "job_4",
      "name": "Merge",
      "flow": "merge-output",
      "source_id": "src_abc123",
      "depends_on": ["job_2", "job_3"]
    &#125;
  ]
&#125;</code></pre>

  <p>The Controller validates the dependency graph for cycles before persisting any jobs. A cyclic dependency returns <code>422 Unprocessable Entity</code>.</p>

  <h3>Query Jobs in a Chain</h3>
  <pre><code>GET /api/v1/job-chains/movie-2024-encode

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
&#123;
  "chain_group": "movie-2024-encode",
  "jobs": [
    &#123; "id": "job_1", "name": "Analysis",        "status": "completed", "depends_on": [] &#125;,
    &#123; "id": "job_2", "name": "Video Encode",    "status": "running",   "depends_on": ["job_1"] &#125;,
    &#123; "id": "job_3", "name": "Audio Normalise", "status": "running",   "depends_on": ["job_1"] &#125;,
    &#123; "id": "job_4", "name": "Merge",           "status": "waiting",   "depends_on": ["job_2", "job_3"] &#125;
  ],
  "overall_status": "running"
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2>The <code>waiting</code> Status</h2>
  <p>
    A job in the <code>waiting</code> state is stored in the database but is invisible to agents. It transitions as follows:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>waiting</code> → <code>queued</code> — All <code>depends_on</code> jobs have reached <code>completed</code>.</li>
    <li><code>waiting</code> → <code>cancelled</code> — Any <code>depends_on</code> job reaches <code>failed</code> or <code>cancelled</code>, triggering auto-cancellation of the dependent (and all its transitive dependents).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Auto-cancellation cascades depth-first through the dependency graph so that no orphaned waiting job is left behind after a failure.
  </p>

  <h2>Dependency Resolution: UnblockDependentJobs</h2>
  <p>
    When a job transitions to <code>completed</code>, the Controller runs the <strong>UnblockDependentJobs</strong> procedure:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>Query the database for all jobs whose <code>depends_on</code> list contains the just-completed job ID.</li>
    <li>For each candidate, check whether every job in its <code>depends_on</code> list is now in the <code>completed</code> state.</li>
    <li>If all dependencies are satisfied, atomically transition the candidate from <code>waiting</code> to <code>queued</code>.</li>
    <li>Emit a <code>job.queued</code> event so that any idle agent polling the queue picks up the newly eligible job immediately.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The procedure is idempotent and runs inside a serialisable transaction to prevent double-dispatch under concurrent completions.
  </p>

  <h2>UI: CreateJobChain Wizard</h2>
  <p>
    The web UI provides a five-step wizard at <strong>Jobs &gt; New Chain</strong>:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Name &amp; Group</strong> — Enter a human-readable name for the chain and optionally specify a custom <code>chain_group</code> identifier. If left blank, a UUID is generated.</li>
    <li><strong>Add Jobs</strong> — Click <strong>+ Add Step</strong> for each job in the pipeline. For each step, choose a flow and a source.</li>
    <li><strong>Define Dependencies</strong> — A visual DAG editor lets you draw dependency arrows between steps. The UI prevents cycles in real time.</li>
    <li><strong>Agent Tags &amp; Priority</strong> — Optionally pin steps to specific agent tag sets or set relative priorities.</li>
    <li><strong>Review &amp; Submit</strong> — A summary table shows all steps with their dependency chains. Click <strong>Submit Chain</strong> to create all jobs atomically.</li>
  </ol>

