  <h2>Cancellation Behaviour</h2>
  <p>
    Cancelling a chain group cancels all jobs in that group that are not already in a terminal state (<code>completed</code>, <code>failed</code>, <code>cancelled</code>). Jobs that are currently <code>running</code> receive a cancel signal; the agent stops encoding, cleans up temporary chunk files, and reports <code>cancelled</code> back to the Controller.
  </p>
  <p>
    You can also cancel a single job within a chain. If the cancelled job has dependents that are still <code>waiting</code>, they are auto-cancelled via the cascade described above. If the cancelled job has no dependents in <code>waiting</code> state, only the target job is affected.
  </p>

  <h2>Error Handling</h2>
  <p>
    When a job in a chain fails, the following behaviour applies:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The failing job transitions to <code>failed</code> with an error reason and FFmpeg stderr excerpt stored in the job record.</li>
    <li>All jobs whose <code>depends_on</code> list includes the failed job — and all transitive dependents — are auto-cancelled.</li>
    <li>Jobs in parallel branches that do not depend on the failing job continue to run unaffected.</li>
    <li>A <code>chain.failed</code> webhook event is emitted for the chain group if any job reaches <code>failed</code>.</li>
    <li>Retrying the failed job (via <code>POST /api/v1/jobs/&#123;id&#125;/retry</code>) resets it and its cancelled dependents to <code>waiting</code> / <code>queued</code> as appropriate, restarting the cascade from that point.</li>
  </ul>
